---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="BeaconGuard Architecture"
  description="BeaconGuard inserts a deterministic control and evidence boundary between enterprise workflows and governed AI, APIs, or automated systems with release management separated from runtime enforcement."
>
  <section class="doc-architecture">
    <h1>System Architecture</h1>

    <p>
      BeaconGuard inserts a deterministic control and evidence boundary between enterprise workflows and governed AI, APIs, or automated systems. Release management is separated from runtime enforcement so every request is evaluated against an approved control set before execution, with verifiable evidence produced for every decision.
    </p>

    <figure class="system-architecture-section">
      <div class="system-architecture-scroll" tabindex="0" aria-label="Architecture diagram: scroll horizontally to inspect">
        <img
          src="/system-architecture.svg"
          alt="BeaconGuard architecture showing governed release management, deterministic runtime enforcement, allow and deny outcomes, and verifiable decision evidence"
          class="system-architecture-img"
          width="1600"
          height="900"
          loading="eager"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <span class="system-architecture-scroll-hint">Scroll horizontally to inspect the architecture diagram</span>
      </div>
      <figcaption class="system-architecture-caption">
        Separation of governed release management, deterministic runtime enforcement, and verifiable evidence.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>What this diagram shows</h2>
      <p>
        The architecture separates BeaconGuard into two governed operating planes.
      </p>
      <p>
        The management plane defines, validates, compiles, approves, signs, and distributes immutable release artifacts through the BeaconGuard Control Plane.
      </p>
      <p>
        The runtime data plane validates and normalizes request context, performs trust, freshness, and replay checks, and evaluates each request deterministically against the active verified release before downstream execution.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every deterministic decision produces a verifiable decision record. Allowed requests proceed to the governed AI, API, or automated system. Denied requests fail closed and do not execute downstream.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>BeaconGuard Control Plane</h2>
      <p>
        The BeaconGuard Control Plane manages the governed release lifecycle for Compliance Playbooks. It separates control definition from runtime enforcement through validation, compilation, approval, immutable release creation, and controlled distribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        A distributed release is not automatically active. It must pass release verification and activation before it becomes the active verified release used by the runtime.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>Deterministic runtime enforcement</h2>
      <p>
        The BeaconGuard Runtime Control Boundary operates in the request path before governed execution.
      </p>
      <p>
        It performs:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>request validation and context normalization;</li>
        <li>trust, freshness, and replay checks;</li>
        <li>deterministic Compliance Playbook evaluation against the active verified release;</li>
        <li>explicit allow or deny enforcement;</li>
        <li>fail-closed handling when required controls or trusted context are invalid, missing, stale, replayed, or outside approved bounds.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Only an allowed request proceeds to the governed AI, API, or automated system.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>Evidence, replay, and verification</h2>
      <p>
        BeaconGuard emits a verifiable decision record for every deterministic result, including allowed and denied requests.
      </p>
      <p>
        The record identifies the decision context, active release identity, control result, and outcome. This evidence supports reconstruction, replay, verification, audit review, incident analysis, and governance reporting.
      </p>
      <p>
        Do not claim that evidence is append-only, cryptographically signed, or tamper-evident unless those guarantees are explicitly supported elsewhere by the authoritative product documentation and implementation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>Trust boundaries</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>What enters the runtime boundary:</strong> normalized request context and required trust signals.</li>
        <li><strong>What governs evaluation:</strong> the active verified release produced through the controlled release lifecycle.</li>
        <li><strong>What BeaconGuard decides:</strong> an explicit deterministic allow or deny result.</li>
        <li><strong>What proceeds downstream:</strong> only requests that receive an allow result.</li>
        <li><strong>What is prevented:</strong> denied requests and requests that fail required validation, trust, freshness, or replay checks.</li>
        <li><strong>What is emitted for verification:</strong> a decision record containing release identity, decision context, control result, and outcome.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>System Connector for non-native integrations</h2>
      <p>
        Some enterprise applications do not natively produce the protocol or context structure required by the BeaconGuard runtime. An optional System Connector can map source protocols and context into the required request format before the request enters the runtime control boundary.
      </p>
      <p>
        The System Connector is not the policy evaluator, does not activate releases, and cannot bypass fail-closed enforcement. Deterministic evaluation and decision evidence remain functions of the BeaconGuard Runtime Control Boundary.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>Reviewer checkpoints</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Confirm that the BeaconGuard Runtime Control Boundary is positioned before governed execution.</li>
        <li>Confirm that Compliance Playbooks pass validation, compilation, approval, and immutable release creation before distribution.</li>
        <li>Confirm that a distributed release is verified and activated before it becomes the active runtime release.</li>
        <li>Confirm that request validation, trust, freshness, and replay checks occur before deterministic evaluation.</li>
        <li>Confirm that allow and deny results originate from deterministic evaluation.</li>
        <li>Confirm that denied requests do not reach the downstream system.</li>
        <li>Confirm that every deterministic result emits a verifiable decision record.</li>
        <li>Confirm that evidence identifies the active release used for the decision.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>What BeaconGuard is not</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>BeaconGuard is not the enterprise system of record.</li>
        <li>BeaconGuard is not the business transaction processor.</li>
        <li>BeaconGuard is not the AI or model host.</li>
        <li>BeaconGuard is not the enterprise application UI.</li>
        <li>The System Connector is not an enforcement bypass.</li>
        <li>The Control Plane is not part of the per-request execution path.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-architecture-section">
      <h2>Relationship to runtime flow</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/how-it-works">How It Works</a></li>
        <li><a href="/trust-assurance">Trust Center</a></li>
        <li><a href="/deployment">Deployment</a></li>
        <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .system-architecture-caption {
    margin: 0.65rem 0 0;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-section {
    width: min(1440px, calc(100vw - 48px));
    max-width: none;
    margin: 3rem 0;
    margin-left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll {
    width: 100%;
    overflow-x: auto;
    overflow-y: hidden;
    overscroll-behavior-inline: contain;
    scrollbar-gutter: stable;
    background: var(--bg-deep, #0b1220);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    min-width: 1050px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll-hint {
    display: none;
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted, #9aa8c0);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }
  
  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .system-architecture-section {
      width: calc(100vw - 24px);
    }
    
    .system-architecture-img {
      width: 1050px;
      min-width: 1050px;
    }
    
    .system-architecture-scroll-hint {
      display: block;
    }
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll::-webkit-scrollbar {
    height: 8px;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll::-webkit-scrollbar-track {
    background: var(--bg-deep, #0b1220);
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb {
    background: var(--border-muted, #2a3a5a);
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  
  .system-architecture-scroll::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb:hover {
    background: var(--accent-muted, #3a8a5a);
  }
</style>